2011        :return: new operator DAG
2012        """
2013        new_sources = [
2014            s.apply_to(a, target_table_key=target_table_key) for s in self.sources
2015        ]
2016        return new_sources[0].drop_columns(column_deletions=self.column_deletions)

2021        if not self.column_deletions == other.column_deletions:
2022            return False
2023        return True
2024
2025    def columns_used_from_sources(self, using: Optional[set] = None) -> List:
2026        """
2027        Get columns used from sources. Internal method.
2028
2029        :param using: optional column restriction.
2030        :return: list of order sets (list parallel to sources).
2031        """
2032        if using is None:
2033            using = set(self.sources[0].column_names)
2034        return [set([c for c in using if c not in self.column_deletions])]

2074class OrderRowsNode(ViewRepresentation):
2075    """
2076    Class representation of .order_rows() method/step.
2077    """
2078
2079    order_columns: List[str]
2080    reverse: List[str]
2081
2082    def __init__(self, source, columns, *, reverse=None, limit=None):
2083        if isinstance(columns, str):
2084            columns = [columns]
2085        self.order_columns = [c for c in columns]
2086        if reverse is None:
2087            reverse = []
2088        if isinstance(reverse, str):
2089            reverse = [reverse]
2090        self.reverse = [c for c in reverse]
2091        self.limit = limit
2092        have = source.column_names
2093        unknown = set(self.order_columns) - set(have)
2094        if len(unknown) > 0:
2095            raise ValueError("missing required columns: " + str(unknown))
2096        not_order = set(self.reverse) - set(self.order_columns)
2097        if len(not_order) > 0:
2098            raise ValueError("columns declared reverse, but not order: " + str(unknown))
2099        ViewRepresentation.__init__(
2100            self,
2101            column_names=source.column_names,
2102            sources=[source],
2103            node_name="OrderRowsNode",
2104        )
2105
2106    def apply_to(self, a, *, target_table_key=None):
2107        """
2108        Apply self to operator DAG a. Basic OperatorPlatform, composable API.
2109
2110        :param a: operators to apply to
2111        :param target_table_key: table key to replace with self, None counts as "match all"
2112        :return: new operator DAG
2113        """
2114        new_sources = [
2115            s.apply_to(a, target_table_key=target_table_key) for s in self.sources
2116        ]
2117        return new_sources[0].order_rows(
2118            columns=self.order_columns, reverse=self.reverse, limit=self.limit
2119        )
2120
2121    def _equiv_nodes(self, other):
2122        if not isinstance(other, OrderRowsNode):
2123            return False
2124        if not self.order_columns == other.order_columns:
2125            return False
2126        if not self.reverse == other.reverse:
2127            return False
2128        if not self.limit == other.limit:
2129            return False
2130        return True
2131
2132    def columns_used_from_sources(self, using: Optional[set] = None) -> List:
2133        """
2134        Get columns used from sources. Internal method.
2135
2136        :param using: optional column restriction.
2137        :return: list of order sets (list parallel to sources).
2138        """
2139        cols = set(self.column_names)
2140        if using is None:
2141            return [cols]
2142        cols = cols.intersection(using).union(self.order_columns)
2143        return [cols]
2144
2145    def to_python_src_(self, *, indent=0, strict=True, print_sources=True):
2146        """
2147        Return text representing operations.
2148
2149        :param indent: additional indent to apply in formatting.
2150        :param strict: if False allow eliding of columns names and other long structures.
2151        :param print_sources: logical, print children.
2152        """
2153        s = ""
2154        if print_sources:
2155            s = (
2156                self.sources[0].to_python_src_(indent=indent, strict=strict)
2157                + "\n"
2158                + " " * (max(indent, 0) + 3)
2159            )
2160        s = s + (".order_rows(" + self.order_columns.__repr__())
2161        if len(self.reverse) > 0:
2162            s = s + ", reverse=" + self.reverse.__repr__()
2163        if self.limit is not None:
2164            s = s + ", limit=" + self.limit.__repr__()
2165        s = s + ")"
2166        return s
2167
2168    def to_near_sql_implementation_(
2169        self, db_model, *, using, temp_id_source, sql_format_options=None
2170    ) -> data_algebra.near_sql.NearSQL:
2171        """
2172        Convert operator dag into NearSQL type for translation to SQL string.
2173
2174        :param db_model: database model
2175        :param using: optional column restriction set
2176        :param temp_id_source: source of temporary ids
2177        :param sql_format_options: options for sql formatting
2178        :return: data_algebra.near_sql.NearSQL
2179        """
2180        return db_model.order_to_near_sql(
2181            self,
2182            using=using,
2183            temp_id_source=temp_id_source,
2184            sql_format_options=sql_format_options,
2185        )
2186
2187    # short-cut main interface
2188
2189    def is_trivial_when_intermediate_(self) -> bool:
2190        """
2191        Return if True if operator can be eliminated from interior of chain.
2192        """
2193        return self.limit is None

2196class MapColumnsNode(ViewRepresentation):
2197    """
2198    Class representation of .map_columns() method/step.
2199    """
2200
2201    column_remapping: Dict[str, str]
2202    column_deletions: List[str]
2203
2204    def __init__(self, source, column_remapping):
2205        self.column_remapping = {k: v for (k, v) in column_remapping.items() if v is not None}
2206        self.column_deletions = [k for (k, v) in column_remapping.items() if v is None]
2207        new_cols = [v for (k, v) in column_remapping.items() if v is not None]
2208        orig_cols = [k for k in column_remapping.keys()]
2209        unknown = set(orig_cols) - set(source.column_names)
2210        if len(unknown) > 0:
2211            raise ValueError("Tried to rename unknown columns: " + str(unknown))
2212        collisions = (
2213            set(source.column_names) - set(new_cols).intersection(orig_cols)
2214        ).intersection(new_cols)
2215        if len(collisions) > 0:
2216            raise ValueError(
2217                "Mapping "
2218                + str(self.column_remapping)
2219                + " collides with existing columns "
2220                + str(collisions)
2221            )
2222        column_names = [
2223            (k if k not in self.column_remapping.keys() else self.column_remapping[k])
2224            for k in source.column_names
2225        ]
2226        self.new_columns = set(new_cols) - set(orig_cols)
2227        ViewRepresentation.__init__(
2228            self,
2229            column_names=column_names,
2230            sources=[source],
2231            node_name="MapColumnsNode",
2232        )
2233
2234    def forbidden_columns(
2235        self, *, forbidden: Optional[Set[str]] = None
2236    ) -> Dict[str, Set[str]]:
2237        """
2238        Determine which columns should not be in source tables
2239        (were not in declared structure, and interfere with column production).
2240
2241        :param forbidden: optional incoming forbids.
2242        :return: dictionary operator keys to forbidden sets.
2243        """
2244        # this is where forbidden columns are introduced
2245        if forbidden is None:
2246            forbidden = set()
2247        new_forbidden = set(forbidden) - self.column_remapping.keys()
2248        new_forbidden.update(self.new_columns)
2249        return self.sources[0].forbidden_columns(forbidden=new_forbidden)
2250
2251    def apply_to(self, a, *, target_table_key=None):
2252        """
2253        Apply self to operator DAG a. Basic OperatorPlatform, composable API.
2254
2255        :param a: operators to apply to
2256        :param target_table_key: table key to replace with self, None counts as "match all"
2257        :return: new operator DAG
2258        """
2259        new_sources = [
2260            s.apply_to(a, target_table_key=target_table_key) for s in self.sources
2261        ]
2262        return new_sources[0].map_columns(column_remapping=self.column_remapping)
2263
2264    def _equiv_nodes(self, other):
2265        if not isinstance(other, MapColumnsNode):
2266            return False
2267        if not (self.column_remapping == other.column_remapping):
2268            return False
2269        if not (self.column_deletions == other.column_deletions):
2270            return False
2271        return True
2272
2273    def columns_used_from_sources(self, using: Optional[set] = None) -> List:
2274        """
2275        Get columns used from sources. Internal method.
2276
2277        :param using: optional column restriction.
2278        :return: list of order sets (list parallel to sources).
2279        """
2280        if using is None:
2281            using_tuple = self.column_names
2282        else:
2283            using_tuple = tuple(using)
2284        cols = [k for k in using_tuple if k ]
2285        reverse_mapping = {v: k for k, v in self.column_remapping.items()}
2286        rev_keys = set(reverse_mapping.keys())
2287        cols = [
2288            (k if k not in rev_keys else reverse_mapping[k])
2289            for k in using_tuple
2290        ] + self.column_deletions
2291        return [OrderedSet(cols)]
2292
2293    def to_python_src_(self, *, indent=0, strict=True, print_sources=True):
2294        """
2295        Return text representing operations.
2296
2297        :param indent: additional indent to apply in formatting.
2298        :param strict: if False allow eliding of columns names and other long structures.
2299        :param print_sources: logical, print children.
2300        """
2301        s = ""
2302        if print_sources:
2303            s = (
2304                self.sources[0].to_python_src_(indent=indent, strict=strict)
2305                + "\n"
2306                + " " * (max(indent, 0) + 3)
2307            )
2308        column_remapping = self.column_remapping.copy()
2309        column_remapping.update({k: None for k in self.column_deletions})
2310        s = s + (".map_columns(" + column_remapping.__repr__() + ")")
2311        return s
2312
2313    def to_near_sql_implementation_(
2314        self, db_model, *, using, temp_id_source, sql_format_options=None
2315    ) -> data_algebra.near_sql.NearSQL:
2316        """
2317        Convert operator dag into NearSQL type for translation to SQL string.
2318
2319        :param db_model: database model
2320        :param using: optional column restriction set
2321        :param temp_id_source: source of temporary ids
2322        :param sql_format_options: options for sql formatting
2323        :return: data_algebra.near_sql.NearSQL
2324        """
2325        return db_model.map_columns_to_near_sql(
2326            self,
2327            using=using,
2328            temp_id_source=temp_id_source,
2329            sql_format_options=sql_format_options,
2330        )

2456            self,
2457            using=using,
2458            temp_id_source=temp_id_source,
2459            sql_format_options=sql_format_options,
2460        )
2461
2462
2463class NaturalJoinNode(ViewRepresentation):
2464    """
2465    Class representation of .natural_join() method/step.
2466    """
2467
2468    on_a: List[str]
2469    on_b: List[str]
2470    jointype: str
2471
2472    def __init__(
2473        self,
2474        a,
2475        b,
2476        *,
2477        on_a: List[str],
2478        on_b: List[str],
2479        jointype: str,
2480        check_all_common_keys_in_equi_spec: bool = False,
2481    ):
2482        # check set of tables is consistent in both sub-dags
2483        a_tables = a.get_tables()
2484        b_tables = b.get_tables()
2485        _assert_tables_defs_consistent(a_tables, b_tables)
2486        assert isinstance(on_a, List)
2487        assert numpy.all([isinstance(v, str) for v in on_a])
2488        assert isinstance(on_b, List)
2489        assert numpy.all([isinstance(v, str) for v in on_b])
2490        assert len(on_a) == len(on_b)
2491        common_table_keys = set(a_tables.keys()).intersection(b_tables.keys())
2492        for k in common_table_keys:
2493            if not a_tables[k].same_table_description_(b_tables[k]):
2494                raise ValueError(
2495                    "Different definition of table object on a/b for: " + k
2496                )
2497        # check columns
2498        column_names = list(a.column_names)
2499        columns_seen = set(column_names)
2500        for ci in b.column_names:
2501            if ci not in columns_seen:
2502                column_names.append(ci)
2503                columns_seen.add(ci)
2504        missing_left = set(on_a) - set(a.column_names)
2505        if len(missing_left) > 0:
2506            raise KeyError("left table missing join keys: " + str(missing_left))
2507        missing_right = set(on_b) - set(b.column_names)
2508        if len(missing_right) > 0:
2509            raise KeyError("right table missing join keys: " + str(missing_right))
2510        if check_all_common_keys_in_equi_spec:
2511            missing_common = (
2512                set(a.column_names).intersection(set(b.column_names)) - set(on_a).intersection(on_b)
2513            )
2514            if len(missing_common) > 0:
2515                raise KeyError(
2516                    "check_all_common_keys_in_equi_spec set, and the following common keys are are not in the on-clause: "
2517                    + str(missing_common)
2518                )
2519        # try to re-use column names if possible, saves space in deeply nested join trees.
2520        column_names = tuple(column_names)
2521        if isinstance(a.column_names, tuple) and (
2522            set(column_names) == set(a.column_names)
2523        ):
2524            column_names = a.column_names
2525        elif isinstance(b.column_names, tuple) and (
2526            set(column_names) == set(b.column_names)
2527        ):
2528            column_names = b.column_names
2529        ViewRepresentation.__init__(
2530            self,
2531            column_names=column_names,
2532            sources=[a, b],
2533            node_name="NaturalJoinNode",
2534        )
2535        self.on_a = on_a
2536        self.on_b = on_b
2537        self.jointype = data_algebra.expr_rep.standardize_join_type(jointype)
2538        if (self.jointype == "CROSS") and (len(self.on_a) != 0):
2539            raise ValueError("CROSS joins must have an empty 'on' list")
2540
2541    def apply_to(self, a, *, target_table_key=None):
2542        """
2543        Apply self to operator DAG a. Basic OperatorPlatform, composable API.
2544
2545        :param a: operators to apply to
2546        :param target_table_key: table key to replace with self, None counts as "match all"
2547        :return: new operator DAG
2548        """
2549        new_sources = [
2550            s.apply_to(a, target_table_key=target_table_key) for s in self.sources
2551        ]
2552        return new_sources[0].natural_join(
2553            b=new_sources[1], on=[(va, vb) for (va, vb) in zip(self.on_a, self.on_b)], jointype=self.jointype
2554        )
2555
2556    def _equiv_nodes(self, other):
2557        if not isinstance(other, NaturalJoinNode):
2558            return False
2559        if not self.on_a == other.on_a:
2560            return False
2561        if not self.on_b == other.on_b:
2562            return False
2563        if not self.jointype == other.jointype:
2564            return False
2565        return True
2566
2567    def columns_used_from_sources(self, using: Optional[set] = None) -> List:
2568        """
2569        Get columns used from sources. Internal method.
2570
2571        :param using: optional column restriction.
2572        :return: list of order sets (list parallel to sources).
2573        """
2574        if using is None:
2575            return [OrderedSet(self.sources[i].column_names) for i in range(2)]
2576        using = using.union(self.on_a).union(self.on_b)
2577        return [
2578            ordered_intersect(self.sources[i].column_names, using) for i in range(2)
2579        ]
2580
2581    def to_python_src_(self, *, indent=0, strict=True, print_sources=True):
2582        """
2583        Return text representing operations.
2584
2585        :param indent: additional indent to apply in formatting.
2586        :param strict: if False allow eliding of columns names and other long structures.
2587        :param print_sources: logical, print children.
2588        """
2589        s = "_0."
2590        if print_sources:
2591            s = (
2592                self.sources[0].to_python_src_(indent=indent, strict=strict)
2593                + "\n"
2594                + " " * (max(indent, 0) + 3)
2595            )
2596        s = s + (".natural_join(b=\n" + " " * (indent + 6))
2597        if print_sources:
2598            s = s + (
2599                self.sources[1].to_python_src_(indent=max(indent, 0) + 6, strict=strict)
2600                + ",\n"
2601                + " " * (max(indent, 0) + 6)
2602            )
2603        else:
2604            s = s + " _1, "
2605        on_arg = _convert_parallel_lists_to_on_clause(self.on_a, self.on_b)
2606        s = s + (
2607            "on=" + on_arg.__repr__() + ", jointype=" + self.jointype.__repr__() + ")"
2608        )
2609        return s
2610
2611    def to_near_sql_implementation_(
2612        self, db_model, *, using, temp_id_source, sql_format_options=None
2613    ) -> data_algebra.near_sql.NearSQL:
2614        """
2615        Convert operator dag into NearSQL type for translation to SQL string.
2616
2617        :param db_model: database model
2618        :param using: optional column restriction set
2619        :param temp_id_source: source of temporary ids
2620        :param sql_format_options: options for sql formatting
2621        :return: data_algebra.near_sql.NearSQL
2622        """
2623        return db_model.natural_join_to_near_sql(
2624            self,
2625            using=using,
2626            temp_id_source=temp_id_source,
2627            sql_format_options=sql_format_options,
2628        )
2629

2638    def __init__(self, a, b, *, id_column="table_name", a_name="a", b_name="b"):
2639        # check set of tables is consistent in both sub-dags
2640        assert isinstance(a, ViewRepresentation)
2641        assert isinstance(b, ViewRepresentation)

2809        """

2813        """
2814        Return text representing operations.

2817        :param strict: if False allow eliding of columns names and other long structures.
2818        :param print_sources: logical, print children.
2819        """
2820        s = ""
2821        if print_sources:
2822            s = (
2823                self.sources[0].to_python_src_(indent=indent, strict=strict)
2824                + "\n"
2825                + " " * (max(indent, 0) + 3)

2827        rm_str = self.record_map.__repr__()
2828        rm_str = re.sub("\n", "\n   ", rm_str)

2833    def to_near_sql_implementation_(
2834        self, db_model, *, using, temp_id_source, sql_format_options=None
2835    ) -> data_algebra.near_sql.NearSQL:
2836        """
2837        Convert operator dag into NearSQL type for translation to SQL string.
2838
2839        :param db_model: database model
2840        :param using: optional column restriction set
2841        :param temp_id_source: source of temporary ids
2842        :param sql_format_options: options for sql formatting
2843        :return: data_algebra.near_sql.NearSQL
2844        """
2845        if temp_id_source is None:
2846            temp_id_source = [0]
2847        # TODO: narrow to what we are using
2848        # TODO: use nearsql instead of strings / lists of strings
2849        near_sql = self.sources[0].to_near_sql_implementation_(
2850            db_model=db_model,
2851            using=None,
2852            temp_id_source=temp_id_source,
2853            sql_format_options=sql_format_options,
2854        )
2855        assert isinstance(near_sql, data_algebra.near_sql.NearSQL)
2856        # claims to use all columns
2857        if self.record_map.blocks_in is not None:
2858            view_name = "convert_records_blocks_in_" + str(temp_id_source[0])
2859            temp_id_source[0] = temp_id_source[0] + 1
2860            pi, si = db_model.blocks_to_row_recs_query_str_list_pair(
2861                record_spec=self.record_map.blocks_in
2862            )
2863            near_sql = data_algebra.near_sql.NearSQLRawQStep(
2864                prefix=pi,
2865                query_name=view_name,
2866                quoted_query_name=db_model.quote_identifier(view_name),
2867                sub_sql=data_algebra.near_sql.NearSQLContainer(near_sql=near_sql),
2868                suffix=si,
2869                annotation="convert records blocks in",
2870                ops_key=None,
2871            )
2872            assert isinstance(near_sql, data_algebra.near_sql.NearSQL)
2873        if self.record_map.blocks_out is not None:
2874            view_name = "convert_records_blocks_out_" + str(temp_id_source[0])
2875            temp_id_source[0] = temp_id_source[0] + 1
2876            pi, si = db_model.row_recs_to_blocks_query_str_list_pair(
2877                record_spec=self.record_map.blocks_out,
2878            )
2879            near_sql = data_algebra.near_sql.NearSQLRawQStep(
2880                prefix=pi,
2881                query_name=view_name,
2882                quoted_query_name=db_model.quote_identifier(view_name),
2883                sub_sql=data_algebra.near_sql.NearSQLContainer(near_sql=near_sql),
2884                suffix=si,
2885                annotation="convert records blocks out",
2886                ops_key=None,
2887            )
2888            assert isinstance(near_sql, data_algebra.near_sql.NearSQL)

2892class SQLNode(ViewRepresentation):
2893    """
2894    Class representation of user SQL step in pipeline. Can be used to start a pipeline instead of a TableDescription.
2895    """
2896
2897    def __init__(
2898        self, *, sql: Union[str, List[str]], column_names: List[str], view_name: str
2899    ):
2900        if isinstance(sql, str):
2901            sql = sql.splitlines(keepends=False)
2902            sql = [v for v in sql if len(v.strip()) > 0]
2903        assert isinstance(sql, list)
2904        assert len(sql) > 0
2905        assert all([isinstance(v, str) for v in sql])
2906        assert isinstance(view_name, str)
2907        self.sql = sql.copy()
2908        self.view_name = view_name
2909        ViewRepresentation.__init__(
2910            self,
2911            column_names=column_names,
2912            node_name="SQLNode",
2913        )
2914
2915    def apply_to(self, a, *, target_table_key=None):
2916        """
2917        Apply self to operator DAG a. Basic OperatorPlatform, composable API.
2918
2919        :param a: operators to apply to
2920        :param target_table_key: table key to replace with self, None counts as "match all"
2921        :return: new operator DAG
2922        """
2923        return self
2924
2925    def _equiv_nodes(self, other):
2926        if not isinstance(other, SQLNode):
2927            return False
2928        if self.view_name != other.view_name:
2929            return False
2930        if self.column_names != other.column_names:
2931            return False
2932        if self.sql != other.sql:
2933            return False
2934        return True
2935
2936    def get_tables(self):
2937        """Get a dictionary of all tables used in an operator DAG,
2938        raise an exception if the values are not consistent."""
2939        return dict()
2940
2941    def columns_used_from_sources(self, using: Optional[set] = None) -> List:
2942        """
2943        Get columns used from sources. Internal method.
2944
2945        :param using: optional column restriction.
2946        :return: list of order sets (list parallel to sources).
2947        """
2948        return []
2949
2950    def to_python_src_(self, *, indent=0, strict=True, print_sources=True):
2951        """
2952        Return text representing operations.
2953
2954        :param indent: additional indent to apply in formatting.
2955        :param strict: if False allow eliding of columns names and other long structures.
2956        :param print_sources: logical, print children.
2957        """
2958        s = (
2959            "SQLNode(sql="
2960            + str(self.sql)
2961            + ", column_names="
2962            + str(self.column_names)
2963            + ", view_name="
2964            + self.view_name.__repr__()
2965            + ")"
2966        )
2967        return s
2968
2969    def to_near_sql_implementation_(
2970        self, db_model, *, using, temp_id_source, sql_format_options=None
2971    ) -> data_algebra.near_sql.NearSQL:
2972        """
2973        Convert operator dag into NearSQL type for translation to SQL string.
2974
2975        :param db_model: database model
2976        :param using: optional column restriction set
2977        :param temp_id_source: source of temporary ids
2978        :param sql_format_options: options for sql formatting
2979        :return: data_algebra.near_sql.NearSQL
2980        """
2981        quoted_query_name = db_model.quote_identifier(self.view_name)
2982        near_sql = data_algebra.near_sql.NearSQLRawQStep(
2983            prefix=self.sql,
2984            query_name=self.view_name,
2985            quoted_query_name=quoted_query_name,
2986            sub_sql=None,
2987            suffix=None,
2988            annotation="user supplied SQL",
2989            add_select=False,
2990            ops_key=None,
2991        )
2992        return near_sql

def pretty_format_python(python_str: str, *, black_mode=None) -> str: 
43def pretty_format_python(python_str: str, *, black_mode=None) -> str:
44    """
45    Format Python code, using black.
46
47    :param python_str: Python code
48    :param black_mode: options for black
49    :return: formatted Python code
50    """
51    assert isinstance(python_str, str)
52    formatted_python = python_str
53    if _have_black:
54        try:
55            if black_mode is None:
56                black_mode = black.FileMode()
57            formatted_python = black.format_str(python_str, mode=black_mode)
58        except Exception:
59            pass
60    return formatted_python

class ViewRepresentation(data_algebra.data_ops_types.OperatorPlatform, abc.ABC): 
135class ViewRepresentation(OperatorPlatform, abc.ABC):
136    """Structure to represent the columns of a query or a table.
137    Abstract base class."""
138
139    column_names: Tuple[str, ...]
140    sources: Tuple[
141        "ViewRepresentation", ...
142    ]  # https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0484/#forward-references
143
144    def __init__(
145        self,
146        column_names: Iterable[str],
147        *,
148        sources: Optional[Iterable["ViewRepresentation"]] = None,
149        node_name: str,
150    ):
151        # don't let instances masquerade as iterables
152        assert not isinstance(column_names, str)
153        assert not isinstance(sources, OperatorPlatform)
154        if not isinstance(column_names, tuple):
155            column_names = tuple(column_names)
156        assert len(column_names) > 0
157        for v in column_names:
158            assert isinstance(v, str)
159        assert len(column_names) == len(set(column_names))
160        self.column_names = column_names
161        if sources is None:
162            sources = ()
163        else:
164            if not isinstance(sources, tuple):
165                sources = tuple(sources)
166        for si in sources:
167            assert isinstance(si, ViewRepresentation)
168        self.sources = sources
169        OperatorPlatform.__init__(self, node_name=node_name)
170
171    def column_map(self) -> collections.OrderedDict:
172        """
173        Build a map of column names to ColumnReferences
174        """
175        res = collections.OrderedDict()
176        for ci in self.column_names:
177            res[ci] = data_algebra.expr_rep.ColumnReference(self, ci)
178        return res
179
180    def merged_rep_id(self) -> str:
181        """
182        String key for lookups.
183        """
184        return "ops+ " + str(id(self))
185
186    # convenience
187
188    def ex(self, *, data_model=None, narrow=True, allow_limited_tables=False):
189        """
190        Evaluate operators with respect to Pandas data frames already stored in the operator chain.
191
192        :param data_model: adaptor to data dialect (Pandas for now)
193        :param narrow: logical, if True don't copy unexpected columns
194        :param allow_limited_tables: logical, if True allow execution on non-complete tables
195        :return: table result
196        """
197        tables = self.get_tables()
198        data_map = dict()
199        for tv in tables.values():
200            assert isinstance(tv, TableDescription)
201            assert tv.head is not None
202            if len(tables) > 1:
203                assert tv.table_name_was_set_by_user
204            if not allow_limited_tables:
205                assert tv.nrows == tv.head.shape[0]
206            data_map[tv.table_name] = tv.head
207        return self.eval(data_map=data_map, data_model=data_model, narrow=narrow)
208
209    # characterization
210
211    def get_tables(self):
212        """Get a dictionary of all tables used in an operator DAG,
213        raise an exception if the values are not consistent."""
214
215        tables = dict()
216        # eliminate recursions by stepping through sources
217        visit_stack = list()
218        visit_stack.append(self)
219        while len(visit_stack) > 0:
220            cursor = visit_stack.pop()
221            if isinstance(cursor, TableDescription):
222                k = cursor.key
223                v = cursor
224                if k in tables.keys():
225                    if not v.same_table_description_(tables[k]):
226                        raise ValueError(
227                            "Table " + k + " has two incompatible representations"
228                        )
229                else:
230                    tables[k] = v
231            else:
232                for s in cursor.sources:
233                    visit_stack.append(s)
234        return tables
235
236    @abc.abstractmethod
237    def columns_used_from_sources(self, using: Optional[set] = None) -> List[str]:
238        """
239        Get columns used from sources. Internal method.
240
241        :param using: optional column restriction.
242        :return: list of order sets (list parallel to sources).
243        """
244
245    def methods_used(self) -> Set[MethodUse]:
246        """
247        Return set of methods used.
248        """
249        res: Set[MethodUse] = set()
250        self.get_method_uses_(res)
251        return res
252
253    def get_method_uses_(self, methods_seen: Set[MethodUse]) -> None:
254        """
255        Implementation of get methods_used(), internal method.
256
257        :params methods_seen: set to collect results in.
258        :return: None
259        """
260        for s in self.sources:
261            s.get_method_uses_(methods_seen)
262
263    def columns_produced(self) -> List[str]:
264        """Return list of columns produced by operator dag."""
265        return list(self.column_names)
266
267    def columns_used_implementation_(
268        self, *, using, columns_currently_using_records
269    ) -> None:
270        """Implementation of columns used calculation, internal method."""
271        self_merged_rep_id = self.merged_rep_id()
272        try:
273            crec = columns_currently_using_records[self_merged_rep_id]
274        except KeyError:
275            crec = set()
276            columns_currently_using_records[self_merged_rep_id] = crec
277        if using is None:
278            crec.update(self.column_names)
279        else:
280            unknown = set(using) - set(self.column_names)
281            if len(unknown) > 0:
282                raise ValueError("asked for unknown columns: " + str(unknown))
283            crec.update(using)
284        cu_list = self.columns_used_from_sources(crec.copy())
285        for i in range(len(self.sources)):
286            self.sources[i].columns_used_implementation_(
287                using=cu_list[i],
288                columns_currently_using_records=columns_currently_using_records,
289            )
290
291    def columns_used(self, *, using=None) -> Dict:
292        """Determine which columns are used from source tables."""
293
294        tables = self.get_tables()
295        columns_currently_using_records = {
296            v.merged_rep_id(): set() for v in tables.values()
297        }
298        self.columns_used_implementation_(
299            using=using, columns_currently_using_records=columns_currently_using_records
300        )
301        columns_used = dict()
302        for k, ti in tables.items():
303            vi = columns_currently_using_records[ti.merged_rep_id()]
304            columns_used[k] = vi.copy()
305        return columns_used
306
307    def forbidden_columns(
308        self, *, forbidden: Optional[Set[str]] = None
309    ) -> Dict[str, Set[str]]:
310        """
311        Determine which columns should not be in source tables
312        (were not in declared structure, and interfere with column production).
313
314        :param forbidden: optional incoming forbids.
315        :return: dictionary operator keys to forbidden sets.
316        """
317        if forbidden is None:
318            forbidden = set()
319        res: Dict[str, Set[str]] = dict()
320        for source in self.sources:
321            forbidden_i = source.forbidden_columns(forbidden=forbidden)
322            for (tk, f) in forbidden_i.items():
323                try:
324                    have = res[tk]
325                except KeyError:
326                    have = set()
327                    res[tk] = have
328                have.update(f)
329        return res
330
331    # printing
332
333    def to_python_src_(self, *, indent=0, strict=True, print_sources=True) -> str:
334        """
335        Return text representing operations. Internal method, allows skipping of sources.
336
337        :param indent: additional indent to apply in formatting.
338        :param strict: if False allow eliding of columns names and other long structures.
339        :param print_sources: logical, print children.
340        """
341        return "ViewRepresentation(" + self.column_names.__repr__() + ")"
342
343    # noinspection PyBroadException
344    def to_python(self, *, indent=0, strict=True, pretty=False, black_mode=None) -> str:
345        """
346        Return Python source code for operations.
347
348        :param indent: extra indent.
349        :param strict: if False allow eliding of columns names and other long structures.
350        :param pretty: if True re-format result with black.
351        :param black_mode: black formatter parameters.
352        """
353        self.columns_used()  # for table consistency check/raise
354        if pretty:
355            strict = True
356        python_str = (
357            "(\n"
358            + self.to_python_src_(indent=indent, strict=strict, print_sources=True)
359            + "\n)\n"
360        )
361        if pretty:
362            python_str = pretty_format_python(python_str, black_mode=black_mode)
363        return python_str
364
365    def __repr__(self):
366        return self.to_python(strict=True, pretty=True)
367
368    def __str__(self):
369        return self.to_python(strict=True, pretty=True)
370
371    # noinspection PyMethodMayBeStatic,PyUnusedLocal
372    @abc.abstractmethod
373    def _equiv_nodes(self, other):
374        """Check if immediate ops structure is equivalent, does not check child nodes"""
375
376    def __eq__(self, other):
377        if not isinstance(other, ViewRepresentation):
378            return False
379        if not type(self) is type(other):
380            return False
381        if not type(other) is type(self):
382            return False
383        if self.node_name != other.node_name:
384            return False
385        if self.column_names != other.column_names:
386            return False
387        if len(self.sources) != len(other.sources):
388            return False
389        if not self._equiv_nodes(other):
390            return False
391        for i in range(len(self.sources)):
392            if not self.sources[i].__eq__(other.sources[i]):
393                return False
394        return True
395
396    def __ne__(self, other):
397        return not self.__eq__(other)
398
399    # query generation
400
401    @abc.abstractmethod
402    def to_near_sql_implementation_(
403        self, db_model, *, using, temp_id_source, sql_format_options=None
404    ) -> data_algebra.near_sql.NearSQL:
405        """
406        Convert operator dag into NearSQL type for translation to SQL string.
407
408        :param db_model: database model
409        :param using: optional column restriction set
410        :param temp_id_source: source of temporary ids
411        :param sql_format_options: options for sql formatting
412        :return: data_algebra.near_sql.NearSQL
413        """
414
415    def to_sql(
416        self,
417        db_model=None,
418        *,
419        sql_format_options=None,
420    ) -> str:
421        """
422        Convert operator dag to SQL.
423
424        :param db_model: database model or handle data_algebra.db_model.DBModel or data_algebra.db_model.DBHandle
425        :param sql_format_options: options for sql formatting
426        :return: string representation of SQL query
427        """
428        if db_model is None:
429            import data_algebra.SQLite  # import late to avoid circular import issue
430
431            db_model = data_algebra.SQLite.SQLiteModel()
432        return db_model.to_sql(
433            ops=self,
434            sql_format_options=sql_format_options,
435        )
436
437    # Pandas realization
438
439    def check_constraints(self, data_model, *, strict=True):
440        """
441        Check tables supplied meet data consistency constraints.
442
443        data_model: dictionary of column name lists.
444        """
445        self.columns_used()  # for table consistency check/raise
446        forbidden = self.forbidden_columns()
447        tables = self.get_tables()
448        missing_tables = set(tables.keys()) - set(data_model.keys())
449        if len(missing_tables) > 0:
450            raise ValueError("missing required tables: " + str(missing_tables))
451        for k in tables.keys():
452            have = set(data_model[k])
453            td = tables[k]
454            missing = set(td.column_names) - have
455            if len(missing) > 0:
456                raise ValueError(
457                    "Table " + k + " missing required columns: " + str(missing)
458                )
459            if strict:
460                cf = set(forbidden[k])
461                excess = cf.intersection(have)
462                if len(excess) > 0:
463                    raise ValueError(
464                        "Table " + k + " has forbidden columns: " + str(excess)
465                    )
466
467    def eval(
468        self,
469        data_map,
470        *,
471        data_model=None,
472        narrow: bool = True
473    ):
474        """
475        Evaluate operators with respect to Pandas data frames.
476
477        :param data_map: map from table names to data frames
478        :param data_model: adaptor to data dialect (Pandas for now)
479        :param narrow: logical, if True don't copy unexpected columns
480        :return: table result
481        """
482
483        if data_map is not None:
484            assert isinstance(data_map, dict)
485        if data_model is None:
486            data_model = data_algebra.default_data_model
487        assert isinstance(data_model, data_algebra.data_model.DataModel)
488        self.columns_used()  # for table consistency check/raise
489        tables = self.get_tables()
490        self.check_constraints(
491            {k: x.columns for (k, x) in data_map.items()}, strict=not narrow
492        )
493        for k in tables.keys():
494            if k not in data_map.keys():
495                raise ValueError("Required table " + k + " not in data_map")
496            else:
497                if not data_model.is_appropriate_data_instance(data_map[k]):
498                    raise ValueError("data_map[" + k + "] was not a usable type")
499        return data_model.eval(op=self, data_map=data_map, narrow=narrow)
500
501    # noinspection PyPep8Naming
502    def transform(
503        self,
504        X,
505        *,
506        data_model=None,
507        narrow: bool = True
508    ):
509        """
510        Apply data transform to a table
511
512        :param X: tale to apply to
513        :param data_model: data model for Pandas execution
514        :param narrow: logical, if True narrow number of result columns to specification
515        :return: transformed data frame
516        """
517        if data_model is None:
518            data_model = data_algebra.default_data_model
519        assert isinstance(data_model, data_algebra.data_model.DataModel)
520        self.columns_used()  # for table consistency check/raise
521        tables = self.get_tables()
522        if len(tables) != 1:
523            raise ValueError(
524                "transform(DataFrame) can only be applied to ops-dags with only one table def"
525            )
526        k = [k for k in tables.keys()][0]
527        # noinspection PyUnresolvedReferences
528        if not data_model.is_appropriate_data_instance(X):
529            raise TypeError("can not apply transform() to type " + str(type(X)))
530        data_map = {k: X}
531        return self.eval(
532            data_map=data_map,
533            data_model=data_model,
534            narrow=narrow
535        )
536
537    # composition (used to eliminate intermediate order nodes)
538
539    def is_trivial_when_intermediate_(self) -> bool:
540        """
541        Return if True if operator can be eliminated from interior chain.
542        """
543        return False
544
545    # return table representation of self
546    def as_table_description(self, table_name: str, *, qualifiers=None):
547        """
548        Return representation of operator as a table description.
549
550        :param table_name: table name to use.
551        :param qualifiers: db qualifiers to annotate
552        """
553        return TableDescription(
554            table_name=table_name,
555            column_names=self.column_names,
556            qualifiers=qualifiers,
557        )
558
559    # implement builders for all non-initial ops types on base class
560    def extend_parsed_(
561        self, parsed_ops, *, partition_by=None, order_by=None, reverse=None
562    ) -> "ViewRepresentation":
563        """
564        Add new derived columns, can replace existing columns for parsed operations. Internal method.
565
566        :param parsed_ops: dictionary of calculations to perform.
567        :param partition_by: optional window partition specification, or 1.
568        :param order_by: optional window ordering specification, or 1.
569        :param reverse: optional order reversal specification.
570        :return: compose operator directed acyclic graph
571        """
572        if (parsed_ops is None) or (len(parsed_ops) < 1):
573            return self
574        partition_by = _work_col_group_arg(
575            partition_by, arg_name="partition_by", columns=self.column_names
576        )
577        order_by = _work_col_group_arg(
578            order_by, arg_name="order_by", columns=self.column_names
579        )
580        reverse = _work_col_group_arg(
581            reverse, arg_name="reverse", columns=self.column_names
582        )
583        assert reverse != 1
584        new_cols_produced_in_calc = set([k for k in parsed_ops.keys()])
585        if (partition_by != 1) and (len(partition_by) > 0):
586            if len(new_cols_produced_in_calc.intersection(partition_by)) > 0:
587                raise ValueError("must not change partition_by columns")
588            if (order_by != 1) and len(
589                set(partition_by).intersection(set(order_by))
590            ) > 0:
591                raise ValueError("order_by and partition_by columns must be disjoint")
592        if len(new_cols_produced_in_calc.intersection(order_by)) > 0:
593            raise ValueError("must not change partition_by columns")
594        if len(set(reverse).difference(order_by)) > 0:
595            raise ValueError("all columns in reverse must be in order_by")
596        if self.is_trivial_when_intermediate_():
597            return self.sources[0].extend_parsed_(
598                parsed_ops=parsed_ops,
599                partition_by=partition_by,
600                order_by=order_by,
601                reverse=reverse,
602            )
603        # see if we can combine nodes
604        if isinstance(self, ExtendNode):
605            compatible_partition = (partition_by == self.partition_by) or (
606                ((partition_by == 1) or (len(partition_by) <= 0))
607                and ((self.partition_by == 1) or (len(self.partition_by) <= 0))
608            )
609            same_windowing = (
610                data_algebra.expr_rep.implies_windowed(parsed_ops)
611                == self.windowed_situation
612            )
613            if (
614                compatible_partition
615                and same_windowing
616                and (order_by == self.order_by)
617                and (reverse == self.reverse)
618            ):
619                new_ops = data_algebra.data_ops_utils.try_to_merge_ops(
620                    self.ops, parsed_ops
621                )
622                if new_ops is not None:
623                    return ExtendNode(
624                        source=self.sources[0],
625                        parsed_ops=new_ops,
626                        partition_by=partition_by,
627                        order_by=order_by,
628                        reverse=reverse,
629                    )
630        # new ops
631        return ExtendNode(
632            source=self,
633            parsed_ops=parsed_ops,
634            partition_by=partition_by,
635            order_by=order_by,
636            reverse=reverse,
637        )
638
639    def extend(
640        self, ops, *, partition_by=None, order_by=None, reverse=None
641    ) -> "ViewRepresentation":
642        """
643        Add new derived columns, can replace existing columns.
644
645        :param ops: dictionary of calculations to perform.
646        :param partition_by: optional window partition specification, or 1.
647        :param order_by: optional window ordering specification, or 1.
648        :param reverse: optional order reversal specification.
649        :return: compose operator directed acyclic graph
650        """
651        parsed_ops = data_algebra.expr_parse.parse_assignments_in_context(
652            ops=ops, view=self
653        )
654        return self.extend_parsed_(
655            parsed_ops=parsed_ops,
656            partition_by=partition_by,
657            order_by=order_by,
658            reverse=reverse,
659        )
660
661    def project_parsed_(
662        self, parsed_ops=None, *, group_by=None
663    ) -> "ViewRepresentation":
664        """
665        Compute projection, or grouped calculation for parsed ops. Internal method.
666
667        :param parsed_ops: dictionary of calculations to perform, can be empty.
668        :param group_by: optional group key(s) specification.
669        :return: compose operator directed acyclic graph
670        """
671
672        group_by = _work_col_group_arg(
673            group_by, arg_name="group_by", columns=self.column_names
674        )
675        assert group_by != 1
676        if ((parsed_ops is None) or (len(parsed_ops) < 1)) and (len(group_by) < 1):
677            raise ValueError("project must have ops or group_by")
678        new_cols_produced_in_calc = set([k for k in parsed_ops.keys()])
679        if len(new_cols_produced_in_calc.intersection(group_by)):
680            raise ValueError("project can not alter grouping columns")
681        if self.is_trivial_when_intermediate_():
682            return self.sources[0].project_parsed_(parsed_ops, group_by=group_by)
683        return ProjectNode(source=self, parsed_ops=parsed_ops, group_by=group_by)
684
685    def project(self, ops=None, *, group_by=None) -> "ViewRepresentation":
686        """
687        Compute projection, or grouped calculation.
688
689        :param ops: dictionary of calculations to perform, can be empty.
690        :param group_by: optional group key(s) specification.
691        :return: compose operator directed acyclic graph
692        """
693        parsed_ops = data_algebra.expr_parse.parse_assignments_in_context(
694            ops=ops, view=self
695        )
696        return self.project_parsed_(parsed_ops=parsed_ops, group_by=group_by)
697
698    def natural_join(
699        self,
700        b,
701        *,
702        on = None,
703        jointype: str,
704        check_all_common_keys_in_equi_spec: bool = False,
705        by = None,
706        check_all_common_keys_in_by: bool = False,
707    ) -> "ViewRepresentation":
708        """
709        Join self (left) results with b (right).
710
711        :param b: second or right table to join to.
712        :param on: column names to enforce equality on (list of column names, list of tuples, or dictionary)
713        :param jointype: name of join type.
714        :param check_all_common_keys_in_equi_spec: if True, raise if any non-equality key columns are common to tables.
715        :param by: synonym for on, only set at most one of on or by (deprecated).
716        :param check_all_common_keys_in_by: synonym for check_all_common_keys_in_equi_spec (deprecated).
717        :return: compose operator directed acyclic graph
718        """
719        assert isinstance(b, ViewRepresentation)
720        assert (on is None) or (by is None)
721        if by is not None:
722            on = by
723        on_a, on_b = _convert_on_clause_to_parallel_lists(on)
724        assert isinstance(jointype, str)
725        assert isinstance(check_all_common_keys_in_equi_spec, bool)
726        assert isinstance(check_all_common_keys_in_by, bool)
727        check_all_common_keys_in_equi_spec = (
728            check_all_common_keys_in_equi_spec or check_all_common_keys_in_by
729        )
730        if self.is_trivial_when_intermediate_():
731            return self.sources[0].natural_join(b, on=on, jointype=jointype)
732        return NaturalJoinNode(
733            a=self,
734            b=b,
735            on_a=on_a,
736            on_b=on_b,
737            jointype=jointype,
738            check_all_common_keys_in_equi_spec=check_all_common_keys_in_equi_spec,
739        )
740
741    def concat_rows(
742        self, b, *, id_column="source_name", a_name="a", b_name="b"
743    ) -> "ViewRepresentation":
744        """
745        Union or concatenate rows of self with rows of b.
746
747        :param b: table with rows to add.
748        :param id_column: optional name for new source identification column.
749        :param a_name: source annotation to use for self/a.
750        :param b_name: source annotation to use for b.
751        :return: compose operator directed acyclic graph
752        """
753        if b is None:
754            return self
755        assert isinstance(b, ViewRepresentation)
756        assert isinstance(id_column, (str, type(None)))
757        assert isinstance(a_name, str)
758        assert isinstance(b_name, str)
759        if self.is_trivial_when_intermediate_():
760            return self.sources[0].concat_rows(
761                b, id_column=id_column, a_name=a_name, b_name=b_name
762            )
763        return ConcatRowsNode(
764            a=self, b=b, id_column=id_column, a_name=a_name, b_name=b_name
765        )
766
767    def select_rows_parsed_(self, parsed_expr) -> "ViewRepresentation":
768        """
769        Select rows matching parsed expr criteria. Internal method.
770
771        :param parsed_expr: logical expression specifying desired rows.
772        :return: compose operator directed acyclic graph
773        """
774        if parsed_expr is None:
775            return self
776        if self.is_trivial_when_intermediate_():
777            return self.sources[0].select_rows_parsed_(parsed_expr=parsed_expr)
778        return SelectRowsNode(source=self, ops=parsed_expr)
779
780    def select_rows(self, expr) -> "ViewRepresentation":
781        """
782        Select rows matching expr criteria.
783
784        :param expr: logical expression specifying desired rows.
785        :return: compose operator directed acyclic graph
786        """
787        if expr is None:
788            return self
789        if isinstance(expr, (list, tuple)):
790            # convert lists to and expressions
791            assert all([isinstance(vi, str) for vi in expr])
792            if len(expr) < 1:
793                return self
794            elif len(expr) == 1:
795                expr = expr[0]
796            else:
797                expr = " and ".join(["(" + vi + ")" for vi in expr])
798        assert isinstance(expr, (str, data_algebra.expr_rep.PreTerm))
799        if self.is_trivial_when_intermediate_():
800            return self.sources[0].select_rows(expr)
801        ops = data_algebra.expr_parse.parse_assignments_in_context(
802            ops={"expr": expr}, view=self
803        )
804
805        def r_walk_expr(opv):
806            """recursively inspect expression types"""
807            if not isinstance(opv, data_algebra.expr_rep.Expression):
808                return
809            for oi in opv.args:
810                r_walk_expr(oi)
811
812        for op in ops.values():
813            r_walk_expr(op)
814        return self.select_rows_parsed_(parsed_expr=ops)
815
816    def drop_columns(self, column_deletions) -> "ViewRepresentation":
817        """
818        Remove columns from result.
819
820        :param column_deletions: list of columns to remove.
821        :return: compose operator directed acyclic graph
822        """
823        if isinstance(column_deletions, str):
824            column_deletions = [column_deletions]
825        else:
826            column_deletions = list(column_deletions)
827        if (column_deletions is None) or (len(column_deletions) < 1):
828            return self
829        if self.is_trivial_when_intermediate_():
830            return self.sources[0].drop_columns(column_deletions)
831        return DropColumnsNode(source=self, column_deletions=column_deletions)
832
833    def select_columns(self, columns) -> "ViewRepresentation":
834        """
835        Narrow to columns in result.
836
837        :param columns: list of columns to keep.
838        :return: compose operator directed acyclic graph
839        """
840        if isinstance(columns, str):
841            columns = [columns]
842        if (columns is None) or (len(columns) < 1):
843            raise ValueError("must select at least one column")
844        if columns == self.column_names:
845            return self
846        if self.is_trivial_when_intermediate_():
847            return self.sources[0].select_columns(columns)
848        if isinstance(self, SelectColumnsNode):
849            return self.sources[0].select_columns(columns)
850        if isinstance(self, DropColumnsNode):
851            return self.sources[0].select_columns(columns)
852        return SelectColumnsNode(source=self, columns=columns)
853
854    def map_columns(self, column_remapping) -> "ViewRepresentation":
855        """
856        Map column names or rename.
857
858        :param column_remapping: dictionary mapping old column sources to new column names (same
859                                 direction as Pandas rename).
860        :return: compose operator directed acyclic graph
861        """
862        if (column_remapping is None) or (len(column_remapping) < 1):
863            return self
864        assert isinstance(column_remapping, dict)
865        if self.is_trivial_when_intermediate_():
866            return self.sources[0].map_columns(column_remapping)
867        return MapColumnsNode(source=self, column_remapping=column_remapping)
868
869    def rename_columns(self, column_remapping) -> "ViewRepresentation":
870        """
871        Rename columns.
872
873        :param column_remapping: dictionary mapping new column names to old column sources (same
874                                 direction as extend).
875        :return: compose operator directed acyclic graph
876        """
877        if (column_remapping is None) or (len(column_remapping) < 1):
878            return self
879        assert isinstance(column_remapping, dict)
880        if self.is_trivial_when_intermediate_():
881            return self.sources[0].rename_columns(column_remapping)
882        return RenameColumnsNode(source=self, column_remapping=column_remapping)
883
884    def order_rows(self, columns, *, reverse=None, limit=None) -> "ViewRepresentation":
885        """
886        Order rows by column set.
887
888        :param columns: columns to order by.
889        :param reverse: optional columns to reverse order.
890        :param limit: optional row limit to impose on result.
891        :return: compose operator directed acyclic graph
892        """
893        if isinstance(columns, str):
894            columns = [columns]
895        if isinstance(reverse, str):
896            reverse = [reverse]
897        if ((columns is None) or (len(columns) < 1)) and (limit is None):
898            return self
899        if self.is_trivial_when_intermediate_():
900            return self.sources[0].order_rows(columns, reverse=reverse, limit=limit)
901        return OrderRowsNode(source=self, columns=columns, reverse=reverse, limit=limit)
902
903    def convert_records(self, record_map) -> "ViewRepresentation":
904        """
905        Apply a record mapping taking blocks_in to blocks_out structures.
906
907        :param record_map: data_algebra.cdata.RecordMap transform specification
908        :return: compose operator directed acyclic graph
909        """
910        if record_map is None:
911            return self
912        if self.is_trivial_when_intermediate_():
913            return self.sources[0].convert_records(record_map)
914        return ConvertRecordsNode(source=self, record_map=record_map)

Structure to represent the columns of a query or a table. Abstract base class.

def ex(self, *, data_model=None, narrow=True, allow_limited_tables=False): 
188    def ex(self, *, data_model=None, narrow=True, allow_limited_tables=False):
189        """
190        Evaluate operators with respect to Pandas data frames already stored in the operator chain.
191
192        :param data_model: adaptor to data dialect (Pandas for now)
193        :param narrow: logical, if True don't copy unexpected columns
194        :param allow_limited_tables: logical, if True allow execution on non-complete tables
195        :return: table result
196        """
197        tables = self.get_tables()
198        data_map = dict()
199        for tv in tables.values():
200            assert isinstance(tv, TableDescription)
201            assert tv.head is not None
202            if len(tables) > 1:
203                assert tv.table_name_was_set_by_user
204            if not allow_limited_tables:
205                assert tv.nrows == tv.head.shape[0]
206            data_map[tv.table_name] = tv.head
207        return self.eval(data_map=data_map, data_model=data_model, narrow=narrow)

def get_tables(self): 
211    def get_tables(self):
212        """Get a dictionary of all tables used in an operator DAG,
213        raise an exception if the values are not consistent."""
214
215        tables = dict()
216        # eliminate recursions by stepping through sources
217        visit_stack = list()
218        visit_stack.append(self)
219        while len(visit_stack) > 0:
220            cursor = visit_stack.pop()
221            if isinstance(cursor, TableDescription):
222                k = cursor.key
223                v = cursor
224                if k in tables.keys():
225                    if not v.same_table_description_(tables[k]):
226                        raise ValueError(
227                            "Table " + k + " has two incompatible representations"
228                        )
229                else:
230                    tables[k] = v
231            else:
232                for s in cursor.sources:
233                    visit_stack.append(s)
234        return tables

Get a dictionary of all tables used in an operator DAG, raise an exception if the values are not consistent.

def columns_used_implementation_(self, *, using, columns_currently_using_records) -> None: 
267    def columns_used_implementation_(
268        self, *, using, columns_currently_using_records
269    ) -> None:
270        """Implementation of columns used calculation, internal method."""
271        self_merged_rep_id = self.merged_rep_id()
272        try:
273            crec = columns_currently_using_records[self_merged_rep_id]
274        except KeyError:
275            crec = set()
276            columns_currently_using_records[self_merged_rep_id] = crec
277        if using is None:
278            crec.update(self.column_names)
279        else:
280            unknown = set(using) - set(self.column_names)
281            if len(unknown) > 0:
282                raise ValueError("asked for unknown columns: " + str(unknown))
283            crec.update(using)
284        cu_list = self.columns_used_from_sources(crec.copy())
285        for i in range(len(self.sources)):
286            self.sources[i].columns_used_implementation_(
287                using=cu_list[i],
288                columns_currently_using_records=columns_currently_using_records,
289            )

Implementation of columns used calculation, internal method.

def columns_used(self, *, using=None) -> Dict: 
291    def columns_used(self, *, using=None) -> Dict:
292        """Determine which columns are used from source tables."""
293
294        tables = self.get_tables()
295        columns_currently_using_records = {
296            v.merged_rep_id(): set() for v in tables.values()
297        }
298        self.columns_used_implementation_(
299            using=using, columns_currently_using_records=columns_currently_using_records
300        )
301        columns_used = dict()
302        for k, ti in tables.items():
303            vi = columns_currently_using_records[ti.merged_rep_id()]
304            columns_used[k] = vi.copy()
305        return columns_used

Determine which columns are used from source tables.

def forbidden_columns(self, *, forbidden: Optional[Set[str]] = None) -> Dict[str, Set[str]]: 
307    def forbidden_columns(
308        self, *, forbidden: Optional[Set[str]] = None
309    ) -> Dict[str, Set[str]]:
310        """
311        Determine which columns should not be in source tables
312        (were not in declared structure, and interfere with column production).
313
314        :param forbidden: optional incoming forbids.
315        :return: dictionary operator keys to forbidden sets.
316        """
317        if forbidden is None:
318            forbidden = set()
319        res: Dict[str, Set[str]] = dict()
320        for source in self.sources:
321            forbidden_i = source.forbidden_columns(forbidden=forbidden)
322            for (tk, f) in forbidden_i.items():
323                try:
324                    have = res[tk]
325                except KeyError:
326                    have = set()
327                    res[tk] = have
328                have.update(f)
329        return res

def check_constraints(self, data_model, *, strict=True): 
439    def check_constraints(self, data_model, *, strict=True):
440        """
441        Check tables supplied meet data consistency constraints.
442
443        data_model: dictionary of column name lists.
444        """
445        self.columns_used()  # for table consistency check/raise
446        forbidden = self.forbidden_columns()
447        tables = self.get_tables()
448        missing_tables = set(tables.keys()) - set(data_model.keys())
449        if len(missing_tables) > 0:
450            raise ValueError("missing required tables: " + str(missing_tables))
451        for k in tables.keys():
452            have = set(data_model[k])
453            td = tables[k]
454            missing = set(td.column_names) - have
455            if len(missing) > 0:
456                raise ValueError(
457                    "Table " + k + " missing required columns: " + str(missing)
458                )
459            if strict:
460                cf = set(forbidden[k])
461                excess = cf.intersection(have)
462                if len(excess) > 0:
463                    raise ValueError(
464                        "Table " + k + " has forbidden columns: " + str(excess)
465                    )

Check tables supplied meet data consistency constraints.

data_model: dictionary of column name lists.

def eval(self, data_map, *, data_model=None, narrow: bool = True): 
467    def eval(
468        self,
469        data_map,
470        *,
471        data_model=None,
472        narrow: bool = True
473    ):
474        """
475        Evaluate operators with respect to Pandas data frames.
476
477        :param data_map: map from table names to data frames
478        :param data_model: adaptor to data dialect (Pandas for now)
479        :param narrow: logical, if True don't copy unexpected columns
480        :return: table result
481        """
482
483        if data_map is not None:
484            assert isinstance(data_map, dict)
485        if data_model is None:
486            data_model = data_algebra.default_data_model
487        assert isinstance(data_model, data_algebra.data_model.DataModel)
488        self.columns_used()  # for table consistency check/raise
489        tables = self.get_tables()
490        self.check_constraints(
491            {k: x.columns for (k, x) in data_map.items()}, strict=not narrow
492        )
493        for k in tables.keys():
494            if k not in data_map.keys():
495                raise ValueError("Required table " + k + " not in data_map")
496            else:
497                if not data_model.is_appropriate_data_instance(data_map[k]):
498                    raise ValueError("data_map[" + k + "] was not a usable type")
499        return data_model.eval(op=self, data_map=data_map, narrow=narrow)

def transform(self, X, *, data_model=None, narrow: bool = True): 
502    def transform(
503        self,
504        X,
505        *,
506        data_model=None,
507        narrow: bool = True
508    ):
509        """
510        Apply data transform to a table
511
512        :param X: tale to apply to
513        :param data_model: data model for Pandas execution
514        :param narrow: logical, if True narrow number of result columns to specification
515        :return: transformed data frame

def extend_parsed_( self, parsed_ops, *, partition_by=None, order_by=None, reverse=None) -> data_algebra.data_ops.ViewRepresentation: 
560    def extend_parsed_(
561        self, parsed_ops, *, partition_by=None, order_by=None, reverse=None
562    ) -> "ViewRepresentation":
563        """
564        Add new derived columns, can replace existing columns for parsed operations. Internal method.
565
566        :param parsed_ops: dictionary of calculations to perform.
567        :param partition_by: optional window partition specification, or 1.
568        :param order_by: optional window ordering specification, or 1.
569        :param reverse: optional order reversal specification.
570        :return: compose operator directed acyclic graph
571        """
572        if (parsed_ops is None) or (len(parsed_ops) < 1):
573            return self
574        partition_by = _work_col_group_arg(
575            partition_by, arg_name="partition_by", columns=self.column_names
576        )
577        order_by = _work_col_group_arg(
578            order_by, arg_name="order_by", columns=self.column_names
579        )
580        reverse = _work_col_group_arg(
581            reverse, arg_name="reverse", columns=self.column_names
582        )
583        assert reverse != 1
584        new_cols_produced_in_calc = set([k for k in parsed_ops.keys()])
585        if (partition_by != 1) and (len(partition_by) > 0):
586            if len(new_cols_produced_in_calc.intersection(partition_by)) > 0:
587                raise ValueError("must not change partition_by columns")
588            if (order_by != 1) and len(
589                set(partition_by).intersection(set(order_by))
590            ) > 0:
591                raise ValueError("order_by and partition_by columns must be disjoint")
592        if len(new_cols_produced_in_calc.intersection(order_by)) > 0:
593            raise ValueError("must not change partition_by columns")
594        if len(set(reverse).difference(order_by)) > 0:
595            raise ValueError("all columns in reverse must be in order_by")
596        if self.is_trivial_when_intermediate_():
597            return self.sources[0].extend_parsed_(
598                parsed_ops=parsed_ops,
599                partition_by=partition_by,
600                order_by=order_by,
601                reverse=reverse,
602            )
603        # see if we can combine nodes
604        if isinstance(self, ExtendNode):
605            compatible_partition = (partition_by == self.partition_by) or (
606                ((partition_by == 1) or (len(partition_by) <= 0))
607                and ((self.partition_by == 1) or (len(self.partition_by) <= 0))
608            )
609            same_windowing = (
610                data_algebra.expr_rep.implies_windowed(parsed_ops)
611                == self.windowed_situation
612            )
613            if (
614                compatible_partition
615                and same_windowing
616                and (order_by == self.order_by)
617                and (reverse == self.reverse)
618            ):
619                new_ops = data_algebra.data_ops_utils.try_to_merge_ops(
620                    self.ops, parsed_ops
621                )
622                if new_ops is not None:
623                    return ExtendNode(
624                        source=self.sources[0],
625                        parsed_ops=new_ops,
626                        partition_by=partition_by,
627                        order_by=order_by,
628                        reverse=reverse,
629                    )
630        # new ops
631        return ExtendNode(
632            source=self,
633            parsed_ops=parsed_ops,
634            partition_by=partition_by,
635            order_by=order_by,
636            reverse=reverse,
637        )

Add new derived columns, can replace existing columns for parsed operations. Internal method.

Parameters
  • parsed_ops: dictionary of calculations to perform.
  • partition_by: optional window partition specification, or 1.
  • order_by: optional window ordering specification, or 1.
  • reverse: optional order reversal specification.
Returns

compose operator directed acyclic graph

def extend( self, ops, *, partition_by=None, order_by=None, reverse=None) -> data_algebra.data_ops.ViewRepresentation: 
639    def extend(
640        self, ops, *, partition_by=None, order_by=None, reverse=None
641    ) -> "ViewRepresentation":
642        """
643        Add new derived columns, can replace existing columns.

645        :param ops: dictionary of calculations to perform.

656            partition_by=partition_by,
657            order_by=order_by,
658            reverse=reverse,

def project_parsed_( self, parsed_ops=None, *, group_by=None) -> data_algebra.data_ops.ViewRepresentation: 
661    def project_parsed_(
662        self, parsed_ops=None, *, group_by=None
663    ) -> "ViewRepresentation":
664        """
665        Compute projection, or grouped calculation for parsed ops. Internal method.
666
667        :param parsed_ops: dictionary of calculations to perform, can be empty.
668        :param group_by: optional group key(s) specification.
669        :return: compose operator directed acyclic graph
670        """
671
672        group_by = _work_col_group_arg(
673            group_by, arg_name="group_by", columns=self.column_names
674        )
675        assert group_by != 1
676        if ((parsed_ops is None) or (len(parsed_ops) < 1)) and (len(group_by) < 1):
677            raise ValueError("project must have ops or group_by")
678        new_cols_produced_in_calc = set([k for k in parsed_ops.keys()])
679        if len(new_cols_produced_in_calc.intersection(group_by)):
680            raise ValueError("project can not alter grouping columns")
681        if self.is_trivial_when_intermediate_():
682            return self.sources[0].project_parsed_(parsed_ops, group_by=group_by)
683        return ProjectNode(source=self, parsed_ops=parsed_ops, group_by=group_by)

Compute projection, or grouped calculation for parsed ops. Internal method.

Parameters
  • parsed_ops: dictionary of calculations to perform, can be empty.
  • group_by: optional group key(s) specification.
Returns

compose operator directed acyclic graph

def project( self, ops=None, *, group_by=None) -> data_algebra.data_ops.ViewRepresentation: 
685    def project(self, ops=None, *, group_by=None) -> "ViewRepresentation":
686        """
687        Compute projection, or grouped calculation.
688
689        :param ops: dictionary of calculations to perform, can be empty.
690        :param group_by: optional group key(s) specification.
691        :return: compose operator directed acyclic graph
692        """
693        parsed_ops = data_algebra.expr_parse.parse_assignments_in_context(
694            ops=ops, view=self
695        )
696        return self.project_parsed_(parsed_ops=parsed_ops, group_by=group_by)

def natural_join( self, b, *, on=None, jointype: str, check_all_common_keys_in_equi_spec: bool = False, by=None, check_all_common_keys_in_by: bool = False) -> data_algebra.data_ops.ViewRepresentation: 
698    def natural_join(
699        self,
700        b,
701        *,
702        on = None,
703        jointype: str,
704        check_all_common_keys_in_equi_spec: bool = False,
705        by = None,
706        check_all_common_keys_in_by: bool = False,
707    ) -> "ViewRepresentation":
708        """
709        Join self (left) results with b (right).
710
711        :param b: second or right table to join to.
712        :param on: column names to enforce equality on (list of column names, list of tuples, or dictionary)
713        :param jointype: name of join type.
714        :param check_all_common_keys_in_equi_spec: if True, raise if any non-equality key columns are common to tables.
715        :param by: synonym for on, only set at most one of on or by (deprecated).
716        :param check_all_common_keys_in_by: synonym for check_all_common_keys_in_equi_spec (deprecated).
717        :return: compose operator directed acyclic graph
718        """
719        assert isinstance(b, ViewRepresentation)
720        assert (on is None) or (by is None)
721        if by is not None:
722            on = by
723        on_a, on_b = _convert_on_clause_to_parallel_lists(on)
724        assert isinstance(jointype, str)
725        assert isinstance(check_all_common_keys_in_equi_spec, bool)
726        assert isinstance(check_all_common_keys_in_by, bool)
727        check_all_common_keys_in_equi_spec = (
728            check_all_common_keys_in_equi_spec or check_all_common_keys_in_by
729        )
730        if self.is_trivial_when_intermediate_():
731            return self.sources[0].natural_join(b, on=on, jointype=jointype)
732        return NaturalJoinNode(
733            a=self,
734            b=b,
735            on_a=on_a,
736            on_b=on_b,
737            jointype=jointype,
738            check_all_common_keys_in_equi_spec=check_all_common_keys_in_equi_spec,
739        )

def select_rows(self, expr) -> data_algebra.data_ops.ViewRepresentation: 
780    def select_rows(self, expr) -> "ViewRepresentation":
781        """
782        Select rows matching expr criteria.
783
784        :param expr: logical expression specifying desired rows.
785        :return: compose operator directed acyclic graph
786        """
787        if expr is None:
788            return self
789        if isinstance(expr, (list, tuple)):
790            # convert lists to and expressions
791            assert all([isinstance(vi, str) for vi in expr])
792            if len(expr) < 1:
793                return self
794            elif len(expr) == 1:
795                expr = expr[0]
796            else:
797                expr = " and ".join(["(" + vi + ")" for vi in expr])
798        assert isinstance(expr, (str, data_algebra.expr_rep.PreTerm))
799        if self.is_trivial_when_intermediate_():
800            return self.sources[0].select_rows(expr)
801        ops = data_algebra.expr_parse.parse_assignments_in_context(
802            ops={"expr": expr}, view=self
803        )
804
805        def r_walk_expr(opv):
806            """recursively inspect expression types"""
807            if not isinstance(opv, data_algebra.expr_rep.Expression):
808                return
809            for oi in opv.args:
810                r_walk_expr(oi)
811
812        for op in ops.values():
813            r_walk_expr(op)
814        return self.select_rows_parsed_(parsed_expr=ops)

Select rows matching expr criteria.

Parameters
  • expr: logical expression specifying desired rows.
Returns

compose operator directed acyclic graph

def drop_columns(self, column_deletions) -> data_algebra.data_ops.ViewRepresentation:

817        """

825        else:

827        if (column_deletions is None) or (len(column_deletions) < 1):
828            return self

def select_columns(self, columns) -> data_algebra.data_ops.ViewRepresentation: 
833    def select_columns(self, columns) -> "ViewRepresentation":
834        """
835        Narrow to columns in result.
836
837        :param columns: list of columns to keep.
838        :return: compose operator directed acyclic graph
839        """
840        if isinstance(columns, str):
841            columns = [columns]
842        if (columns is None) or (len(columns) < 1):
843            raise ValueError("must select at least one column")
844        if columns == self.column_names:
845            return self
846        if self.is_trivial_when_intermediate_():
847            return self.sources[0].select_columns(columns)
848        if isinstance(self, SelectColumnsNode):
849            return self.sources[0].select_columns(columns)
850        if isinstance(self, DropColumnsNode):
851            return self.sources[0].select_columns(columns)
852        return SelectColumnsNode(source=self, columns=columns)
